BA1.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Missense variant in a gene for which primarily truncating variants are known to cause disease

BP1.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Observed in trans with a pathogenic variant for a fully penetrant dominant gene/disorder or observed in cis with a pathogenic variant in any inheritance pattern

BP2.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: In-frame deletions/insertions in a repetitive region without a known function

BP3.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Multiple lines of computational evidence suggest no impact on gene or gene product (conservation, evolutionary, splicing impact, etc.)

BP4.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Variant found in a case with an alternate molecular basis for disease

BP5.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Reputable source recently reports variant as benign, but the evidence is not available to the laboratory to perform an independent evaluation

BP6.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: A synonymous (silent) variant for which splicing prediction algorithms predict no impact to the splice consensus sequence nor the creation of a new splice site AND the nucleotide is not highly conserved

BP7.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Allele frequency is greater than expected for disorder

BS1.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Observed in a healthy adult individual for a recessive (homozygous), dominant (heterozygous), or X-linked (hemizygous) disorder, with full penetrance expected at an early age

BS2.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Well-established in vitro or in vivo functional studies show no damaging effect on protein function or splicing

BS3.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Lack of segregation in affected members of a family

BS4.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Located in a mutational hot spot and/or critical and well-established functional domain (e.g., active site of an enzyme) without benign variation

PM1.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Absent from controls (or at extremely low frequency if recessive) in Exome Sequencing Project, 1000 Genomes Project, or Exome Aggregation Consortium

PM2.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: For recessive disorders, detected in trans with a pathogenic variant

PM3.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Protein length changes as a result of in-frame deletions/insertions in a nonrepeat region or stop-loss variants

PM4.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Novel missense change at an amino acid residue where a different missense change determined to be pathogenic has been seen before

PM5.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Assumed de novo, but without confirmation of paternity and maternity

PM6.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

Z-score from Wilcoxon rank sum test of Alt Vs. Ref base qualities
Cosegregation with disease in multiple affected family members in a gene definitively known to cause the disease

PP1.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Missense variant in a gene that has a low rate of benign missense variation and in which missense variants are a common mechanism of disease

PP2.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Multiple lines of computational evidence support a deleterious effect on the gene or gene product (conservation, evolutionary, splicing impact, etc.)

PP3.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Patient's phenotype or family history is highly specific for a disease with a single genetic etiology

PP4.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Reputable source recently reports variant as pathogenic, but the evidence is not available to the laboratory to perform an independent evaluation

PP5.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Same amino acid change as a previously established pathogenic variant regardless of nucleotide change

PS1.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: De novo (both maternity and paternity confirmed) in a patient with the disease and no family history

PS2.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: Well-established in vitro or in vivo functional studies supportive of a damaging effect on the gene or gene product

PS3.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: The prevalence of the variant in affected individuals is significantly increased compared with the prevalence in controls

PS4.panel: Clinical Interpretation of genetic variants by ACMG/AMP 2015 guideline

filters.tooltip: null variant (nonsense, frameshift, canonical +- 2 splice sites, initiation codon, single or multiexon deletion) in a gene where LOF is a known mechanism of disease
